The timeline of an interactive video is determined in part by a fixed sequence of scenes and by user interactions. This timeline can be created by connecting scenes in a Storyboard and inserting interactive elements into a scene that change the timeline dynamically.

This article takes a closer look at connecting scenes and adding interactive elements which may alter the timeline of the video dynamically.

## Connect two scenes
To connect individual scenes in a Storyboard:

- **Open the Storyboard editor** and select a Storyboard.

- **Add at least two scenes** from the sidebar to the Storyboard. They will display pink connection indicators. Unconnected scenes also have a red outline to indicate that they are missing connections.

- **Drag-and-drop a connection** between the two scenes. Start from the right-hand side connection indicator of the first scene and snap to the left-hand side connection indicator of the second scene.

A dashed connector line will appear between the two scenes to indicate the sequence in which they will be replayed.

![Storyboard showing scenes with highlighted elements and a website link for navigation.](data:image/png;base64,)

> Connectors and playback order

Each scene in a Storyboard has two pink connection indicators - one on the left-hand side and one on the right-hand side. The order in which these indicators are connected determines the playback order of the scenes in the finalized Pvideo. The playback order follows the dotted connection line from left to right, meaning that if scene A is connected from its right-hand side indicator to the left-hand side indicator of scene B, the playback order will be scene A  scene B.

## Integrate a pop-up
Pop-ups are optional sections of a Pvideo and are only displayed if the viewer intentionally interacts with them. They may be used to show a more in-depth data view of a chart, for example.

Heres how to insert a pop-up into the timeline of an interactive video:

- **Open the scene editor** of the scene that should lead to the pop-up.

- **Go to Interactions** and add a **Call to Action **element.

- **Open the settings** of the **Call to Action** element. Under **Event** &gt; **Event type**, select *Open Popup* from the drop-down menu.

- **Save the scene** and return to the **Storyboard editor**. The Call to Action element will now display a blue connection indicator.

- **Add a pop-up** from the sidebar to the Storyboard. It will also display a blue connection indicator.

- **Drag-and-drop a connection** between the Call to Action element and the pop-up. A dashed connector line will appear between them to indicate the connection.

![Storyboard layout featuring scenes and a popup for a video project.](data:image/png;base64,)

> Tip: Add a return button to a pop-up

After the pop-up has finished playing, it wont automatically return to the main video. This means that the pop-up will be the last frame of the interactive video, unless a return button is added to it.

If the pop-up should not be the last frame of the interactive video, for example because it contains some scenes that should be played after the pop-up, make sure to add a **Call to Action** element to the pop-up with the **Event type** set to *Close Popup*. By interacting with this CTA button, the viewer will be returned to the same timestamp at which they previously opened the pop-up.

## Remove connections
To remove a connection, select the dashed connector line in the Storyboard and press the *Delete* key. The dashed connector line will be removed.

### FAQ
#### I have dragged the connector line to the wrong scene in the Storyboard. How can I change it?
Its not possible to retroactively change the start or end point of an established connection, for example by drag-and-dropping the end point to a different scene. Instead, remove the old connection first and create a new one between the correct scenes.
